Hennigan</a\n> and <a itemprop=\"author\" href=\"/la-bio-tracy-wilkinson-staff.html#nt=byline\" class=\"trb_ar_by_nm_au_a\">Tracy Wilkinson</a\n></span\n          ><span class=\"trb_ar_by_b\"></span\n      ><a class=\"trb_ar_by_cl\" href=\"mailto:william.hennigan@latimes.com,tracy.wilkinson@latimes.com?subject=Regarding: &quot;U.S. launches dozens of missiles in response to chemical weapons attack&quot;\" data-role=\"sc_sEmail\">Contact Reporters</a\n    ></span\n    ></div\n  ><div class=\"trb_ar_dateline\"><time itemprop=\"datePublished\" class=\"trb_ar_dateline_time\" data-dt=\"April 6, 2017, 8:25 PM\" datetime=\"2017-04-06T20:25:00PDT\"></time>\n  <span data-content-dateline=\"Reporting from Washington\" class=\"trb_ar_dateline_line\"></span></div>\n    </div>\n            <div itemprop=\"articleBody\">\n                    \n                        <div class=\"trb_ar_page\"  data-role=\"pagination_page\" data-content-page=\"1\">\n                          \n      <p>The Pentagon launched dozens of cruise missiles against an airfield in central Syria late Thursday in retaliation for a gruesome poison gas attack this week that U.S. officials said was carried out by President Bashar Assad\u2019s forces.</p><p>President Trump authorized the attack, the most significant military action of his 11-week presidency, after he was briefed by Defense Secretary James N. Mattis in Palm Beach, Fla., where the president is hosting Chinese President Xi Jinping.</p><div class=\"trb_gptAd trb_ar_main_ad\" data-role=\"adloader adloader_ad delayload delayload_done\" data-adloader-size=\"300x250\" data-state=\"adloader_unloaded\"  data-withinviewport-options=\"bottomOffset=100&topOffset=1000000\"  data-adloader-position=\"articleCube\" data-adloader-adtype=\"articlebottomcube\" data-adloader-label ></div\n       >\n  <p>\u201cAssad choked out the lives of helpless men, women and children,\u201d Trump said in a televised statement from his Mar-a-Lago retreat. \u201cEven beautiful babies were cruelly murdered at this very barbaric attack. No child of God should ever suffer such horror.\u201d</p><p>\u201cTonight I ordered a targeted military strike on the airfield in Syria from where the chemical attack was launched,\u201d he added. \u201cIt is in this vital national security interest of the United States to prevent and deter the spread and use of deadly chemical weapons.\u201d</p><div class=\"trb_ar_cont\" data-ar-cont=\"Article continues below\"></div>\n            <aside class=\"trb_ar_sponsoredmod\" data-v-ymid=\"ym_1082601812867266781\" data-adloader-networktype=\"yieldmo\" data-role=\"delayload delayload_item\" data-screen-size='mobile' data-withinviewport-options=\"bottomOffset=100&topOffset=1000000\" data-load-method=\"trb.vendor.yieldmo.init\" data-load-type=\"method\" >\n            </aside><aside class=\"trb_ar_sponsoredmod trb_barker_mediaconductor\" data-adloader-networktype=\"mediaconductor\" data-role=\"delayload delayload_item\" data-screen-size='desktop' data-withinviewport-options=\"bottomOffset=100\" data-load-method=\"trb.vendor.mediaconductor.init\" data-load-type=\"method\"  data-vendor-mc></aside><p>The attack marks the first time the U.S. has deliberately targeted Assad's military in Syria's multi-sided civil war, now in its seventh year. Until now, the U.S. has focused only on targeting Islamic State militants.</p><p>It marked a violent and abrupt reversal of Trump\u2019s previous hands-off stance toward Assad.</p><p>In effect, Trump was carrying out the policy that his predecessor, Barack Obama, had nearly executed, but backed away from, in the fall of 2013 after an even more deadly chemical weapons attack on civilians.</p><p>At the time, Trump had publicly urged Obama not to strike, saying that to do so without congressional approval would be a mistake.</p><div class=\"trb_ar_cont\" data-ar-cont=\"Article continues below\"></div>\n  \t\t        \n                  <aside class=\"trb_ar_sponsoredmod\" data-adloader-networktype=\"yieldmo\" data-v-ymid=\"ym_1606464552242100545\" data-role=\"delayload delayload_item\"  data-withinviewport-options=\"bottomOffset=100\" data-load-method=\"trb.vendor.yieldmo.init\" data-load-type=\"method\" >\n                  </aside><p>But people who have spoken to Trump say he was deeply affected by the images of children choking to death as a result of the attack, which Turkish medical authorities, who treated many of the victims, said involved sarin nerve gas.</p><p>Trump said in a brief news conference this week that the attack had caused him to change his views about Assad.</p><p>\u201cThat crosses many, many lines,\u201d Trump said Wednesday. \u201cBeyond a red line \u2014 many, many lines.\u201d</p><p>The strike was carried out by two Navy destroyers patrolling in the eastern Mediterranean Sea, which fired roughly 60 Tomahawk cruise missiles from hundreds of miles offshore, well out of range of Syrian air defenses, officials said.</p><div class=\"trb_ar_cont\" data-ar-cont=\"Article continues below\"></div>\n  <aside class=\"trb_embed\" data-content-id=\"92993881\" data-content-size=\"large\" data-content-type=\"image\" data-content-slug=\"la-fg-tomahawk-img-20170406\" data-content-subtype=\"photo\" data-role=\"sc_item imgsize_ratiosizecontainer lightbox_container \" data-state=\"\" data-embed-id=\"92993881\">        <div class=\"trb_embed_modalBox\"><span class=\"trb_embed_media_close\" data-role=\"lightbox_close\"></span><div class=\"trb_embed_media\">         <span class=\"trb_embed_media_info\" data-role=\"embed_info lightbox_info\"></span><figure data-role=\" delayload  delayload_done imgsize_item\" class=\"trb_embed_imageContainer_figure\"><img itemprop=\"image\" data-baseurl=\"http://www.trbimg.com/img-58e6fda1/turbine/la-fg-tomahawk-img-20170406\" alt=\"Tomahawk missile\" class=\"trb_embed_imageContainer_img\" title=\"Tomahawk missile\" data-c-nd=\"1300x730\" /></figure><span class=\"trb_embed_media_open\" data-role=\"lightbox_open\"></span><div class=\"trb_embed_related\"  data-role=\"lightbox_metadata\" >  <span class=\"trb_embed_related_title\">Tomahawk missile</span>    <div class=\"trb_embed_related_credit_and_caption\"></div>  <div class=\"trb_sc\" data-role=\"sc_information sc_container\" data-sc-c=\"page\" data-sc-url=\"/visuals/graphics/la-fg-tomahawk-img-20170406-photo.html\" data-sc-ti=\"Tomahawk missile\" data-sc-th=\"http://www.trbimg.com/img-58e6fda1/turbine/la-fg-tomahawk-img-20170406\" data-sc-sl=\"la-fg-tomahawk-img-20170406\" data-sc-cont=\"photo\" data-sc-nn=\"Los Angeles Times\" data-sc-contid=\"92993881\"><span class=\"trb_sc_item\" data-role=\"sc_share\" data-sc-t=\"facebook\" ></span  ><span class=\"trb_sc_item\" data-role=\"sc_share\" data-sc-t=\"twitter\" ></span  ><span class=\"trb_sc_item\" data-role=\"sc_email\" data-sc-t=\"email\" ></span  ></div      ></div>         <div class=\"trb_gptAd\" data-role=\"adloader adloader_ad\" data-adloader-size=\"300x250\" data-state=\"adloader_unloaded\"  data-withinviewport-options=\"bottomOffset=100\"  data-adloader-position=\"lightBoxCube\" data-adloader-adtype=\"cube\" data-adloader-positionoverride=\"lb\" data-adloader-label ></div       >    </div>    </div></aside><p>The Porter, a destroyer that launched Tomahawk missiles during the opening stage of the 2003 invasion of Iraq, is in the region, along with the guided missile destroyer Ross.</p><p>The target was a military airfield, Shayrat, northeast of Damascus, that U.S. officials said was used to launch the lethal gas attack in Idlib Province on Tuesday. The field has two runways and a series of hardened shelters.</p><p>Targets included aircraft, fuel and weapons depots, and command and control facilities, officials said. Pentagon officials said they were assessing the results of the strikes, which hit the base before dawn Friday in Syria. </p><p>The strike was designed to be limited in nature and to damage facilities with minimal casualties, the officials made clear.</p><p>\u201cEvery precaution was taken to execute this strike with minimal risk to personnel at the airfield,\u201d Capt. Jeff Davis, a Pentagon spokesman, told reporters. \u201cThe strike was a proportional response.\u201d </p><p>The Russian military, which operates from the Shayrat base, was warned ahead of time, Davis said, and the area that the Russians are known to have used was carefully not targeted.</p><p>The U.S. has no plans for additional strikes for now, he added.</p><p>\u201cIt will be the regime\u2019s choice if there are any more\u201d military strikes,\u201d Davis said. \u201cAnd it will be based upon their conduct going forward. We do not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against innocent civilians.\u201d</p><p>The action drew mixed responses from leaders of both parties, who have been deeply divided over Syria policy nearly for the length of the country\u2019s civil war.</p><p>Members of Congress who have long argued for more direct U.S. military action against Assad, including Republican Sens. John McCain of Arizona and Marco Rubio of Florida, hailed the attack.</p><p>House Speaker Paul Ryan (R-Wis.) said the strike &quot;was appropriate and just.\u201d</p><p>\u201cThese tactical strikes make clear that the Assad regime can no longer count on American inaction as it carries out atrocities against the Syrian people,\u201d he said.</p><p>Hillary Clinton, whom Trump defeated in the presidential election, said in an appearance in New York several hours before the strikes were launched that she had long advocated attacking Syria\u2019s airfields.</p><p>But other Democrats chided Trump for acting without Congress\u2019 approval.</p><p>So did Sen. Rand Paul (R-Ky.). &quot;While we all condemn the atrocities in Syria, the United States was not attacked,\u201d he said.</p><p>\u201cThe President needs Congressional authorization for military action as required by the Constitution, and I call on him to come to Congress for a proper debate.\u201d</p><p>\u201cOur prior interventions in this region have done nothing to make us safer, and Syria will be no different,&quot; he said. </p>\n  <aside class=\"trb_embed\"  data-content-size=\"large\" data-content-type=\"blurb\"\n      ><div id=\"trb_em_b_92993496\" class=\"trb_embed_blurb\" xlink:href=\"#City_bullet\" y=\"-8.2\"> \n    </use> \n    <use height=\"16.5\" style=\"overflow:visible;\" transform=\"matrix(1 0 0 -1 505.6683 390.6669)\" width=\"16.5\" x=\"-8.2\" xlink:href=\"#Country_capital\" y=\"-16\"> \n    </use> \n    <use height=\"31.9\" style=\"overflow:visible;\" transform=\"matrix(1 0 0 -1 367.5405 505.9994)\" width=\"31.9\" x=\"-16\" xlink:href=\"#Country_capital\" y=\"-16\"> \n    </use> \n    <g id=\"Pointer_box_headline_2_\"> \n     <polygon class=\"st15\" points=\"541.8,558.5 927.9,558.5 927.9,458.6 589.2,458.6 527.8,422.2 574.3,458.6 541.8,458.6 \t\t\"> \n     </polygon> \n     <rect class=\"st6\" height=\"88.7\" width=\"357.4\" x=\"561.6\" y=\"463.7\"> \n     </rect> \n     <text transform=\"matrix(1 0 0 1 561.591 499.229)\"> \n      <tspan class=\"st16 st10 st17\" x=\"0\" y=\"0\">\n        Shayrat air base, \n      </tspan> \n      <tspan class=\"st16 st10 st17\" x=\"0\" y=\"42\">\n        site of U.S. airstrike \n      </tspan> \n     </text> \n    </g> \n    <use height=\"10.8\" style=\"overflow:visible;\" transform=\"matrix(3.1135 0 0 -3.1135 528.8799 422.8587)\" width=\"10.8\" x=\"-5.4\" xlink:href=\"#Explosion_2\" y=\"-5.4\"> \n    </use> \n   </g> \n   <g id=\"META_-_DATA\"> \n   </g> \n   <script>  var rects = document.querySelectorAll('.reference-rect');        if (rects.length > 0) {            for (var i = 0; i < rects.length; i++) {                var rect = rects[i];                var par = rect.parentNode;                var img = document.createElementNS('http://www.w3.org/2000/svg', 'image');                var imgHeight = rect.getAttribute('height');                var imgWidth = rect.getAttribute('width');                var transform = rect.getAttribute('transform');                var b64img = rect.getAttribute('xlink:href');                img.setAttributeNS(null, 'height', imgHeight);                img.setAttributeNS(null, 'width', imgWidth);                img.setAttributeNS(null, 'transform', transform);                img.setAttributeNS('http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink','href', b64img);                par.insertBefore(img, par.childNodes[0]);                par.removeChild(rect);            }        } </script>\n  </svg>\n </body>\n</html> --></div>\n</aside\n  ><p>Pentagon officials updated their Syria plans after an emergency meeting of the National Security Council late Wednesday, one day after U.S radar and surveillance systems detected a fixed-wing Syrian aircraft drop bombs near a hospital in the rebel-held area around Khan Sheikhoun in Idlib province, officials said.</p><p>Soon after the attack, photos and videos emerged on social media that showed lifeless bodies of children, eyes open, sprawled on the ground beside surviving victims with foam bubbling from their mouths as they gasped for air.</p><p>The Joint Chiefs of Staff met Thursday afternoon to consider the crisis and top congressional officials were briefed on the plans. The White House national security advisor, H.R. McMaster, was in Palm Beach with Trump.</p><p>Whether the strike Thursday will seriously affect Syria\u2019s capabilities remains to be seen.</p><p>Airstrikes on the runways that Syrian forces use to launch bombing missions would have only temporary, minimal impact, experts said.</p><p>Helicopters, which Syrian troops have used to drop improvised \u201cbarrel bombs\u201d on civilian targets, can fly from almost anywhere.</p><p>Complicating the calculus, more than 1,000 U.S. troops now are deployed in Syria. Many are helping Syrian rebel militias fight against Islamic State, especially as they close in on the group\u2019s stronghold at Raqqah.</p><p>The U.S. attack could make the Americans targets for retaliation from Syrian troops.</p><p>In any case, a \u201cone-off strike\u201d would have no real impact, said Frederic C. Hof, a former Obama administration advisor on Syria and director of the Rafik Hariri Center for the Middle East at the Atlantic Council in Washington.</p><p>\u201cIt\u2019s basically telling Assad \u2018Do what you want to civilians, just not with chemicals,\u2019\u201d he said. \u201cWe\u2019ll go back to where we were in 2013.\u201d</p></div>\n                      \n                        <div class=\"trb_ar_page\"  data-role=\"pagination_page\" data-content-page=\"2\">\n                          <p>Any attack needs to be coupled with a diplomatic effort to get Russia to rein in Assad\u2019s targeting of schools, marketplaces, and apartment blocks, Hof said, adding that \u201cotherwise, Assad will return to business as usual.\u201d</p><p>The options in Syria also have become more complex since 2015 because Russian and Iranian forces have poured in to help Assad. Any broader attack on his forces risks a confrontation with Russia, a nuclear-powered rival that Trump had hoped to recruit for the fight against Islamic State.</p><div class=\"trb_gptAd trb_ar_main_ad\" data-role=\"adloader adloader_ad delayload delayload_done\" data-adloader-size=\"300x250\" data-state=\"adloader_unloaded\"  data-withinviewport-options=\"bottomOffset=100\"  data-adloader-position=\"articleCube\" data-adloader-adtype=\"articlebottomcube\" data-adloader-label ></div\n       >\n  <p>There were indications that the administration was losing patience with Russia.</p><p>\u201cIt is very important that [the Russians] consider carefully their continued support for the Assad regime,\u201d Secretary of State Rex Tillerson told reporters.</p><p>Tillerson added there was \u201cno doubt in our minds\u201d that Assad\u2019s government was responsible for the poison gas attack. He said there is \u201cno role\u201d for Assad in Syria\u2019s future, reversing the position he had expressed last week.</p><p>Tillerson will visit Moscow next week. Although the trip was previously planned, it will focus in part on Russia\u2019s continued support for Assad, officials said Thursday.</p><p>Tillerson called his Russian counterpart, Sergei Lavrov, on Wednesday to hear Russia\u2019s version of the Syria attack, a senior State Department official said.</p><p>Moscow has backed Assad\u2019s claims that Syrian forces were not responsible, saying the toxic gas was released in an airstrike on a rebel storage facility.</p><p>At the United Nations Security Council, a draft resolution by the United States, France and Great Britain that condemns Assad was revised slightly on Russian insistence. </p><p>But Russia is likely to veto it, as it vetoed previous measures against Syria\u2019s use of chemical weapons.</p><div class=\"trb_ar_cont\" data-ar-cont=\"Article continues below\"></div>\n  <aside class=\"trb_embed\"  data-content-size=\"large\" data-content-type=\"blurb\"\n      ><div id=\"trb_em_b_90893636\" class=\"trb_embed_blurb\" .trb_embed_media_next:before,[data-state~=lightbox_lightboxOpen] .trb_backplate [data-role~=carousel_view] .trb_embed_media_prev:before{padding:12px 0}</script>\n<script type=\"trb/css\" data-css-key=videoscroll>\n</script>\n</body>\n</html>", "title": "U.S. launches dozens of missiles in response to chemical weapons attack", "url": "http://www.latimes.com/la-fg-syria-us-20170406-story.html", "date": "04-06-2017", "source": "latimes", "text": "The Pentagon launched dozens of cruise missiles against an airfield in central Syria late Thursday in retaliation for a gruesome poison gas attack this week that U.S. officials said was carried out by President Bashar Assad\u2019s forces.\n\nPresident Trump authorized the attack, the most significant military action of his 11-week presidency, after he was briefed by Defense Secretary James N. Mattis in Palm Beach, Fla., where the president is hosting Chinese President Xi Jinping.\n\n\u201cAssad choked out the lives of helpless men, women and children,\u201d Trump said in a televised statement from his Mar-a-Lago retreat. \u201cEven beautiful babies were cruelly murdered at this very barbaric attack. No child of God should ever suffer such horror.\u201d\n\n\u201cTonight I ordered a targeted military strike on the airfield in Syria from where the chemical attack was launched,\u201d he added. \u201cIt is in this vital national security interest of the United States to prevent and deter the spread and use of deadly chemical weapons.\u201d\n\nThe attack marks the first time the U.S. has deliberately targeted Assad's military in Syria's multi-sided civil war, now in its seventh year. Until now, the U.S. has focused only on targeting Islamic State militants.\n\nIt marked a violent and abrupt reversal of Trump\u2019s previous hands-off stance toward Assad.\n\nIn effect, Trump was carrying out the policy that his predecessor, Barack Obama, had nearly executed, but backed away from, in the fall of 2013 after an even more deadly chemical weapons attack on civilians.\n\nAt the time, Trump had publicly urged Obama not to strike, saying that to do so without congressional approval would be a mistake.\n\nBut people who have spoken to Trump say he was deeply affected by the images of children choking to death as a result of the attack, which Turkish medical authorities, who treated many of the victims, said involved sarin nerve gas.\n\nTrump said in a brief news conference this week that the attack had caused him to change his views about Assad.\n\n\u201cThat crosses many, many lines,\u201d Trump said Wednesday. \u201cBeyond a red line \u2014 many, many lines.\u201d\n\nThe strike was carried out by two Navy destroyers patrolling in the eastern Mediterranean Sea, which fired roughly 60 Tomahawk cruise missiles from hundreds of miles offshore, well out of range of Syrian air defenses, officials said.\n\nTomahawk missile\n\nThe Porter, a destroyer that launched Tomahawk missiles during the opening stage of the 2003 invasion of Iraq, is in the region, along with the guided missile destroyer Ross.\n\nThe target was a military airfield, Shayrat, northeast of Damascus, that U.S. officials said was used to launch the lethal gas attack in Idlib Province on Tuesday. The field has two runways and a series of hardened shelters.\n\nTargets included aircraft, fuel and weapons depots, and command and control facilities, officials said. Pentagon officials said they were assessing the results of the strikes, which hit the base before dawn Friday in Syria.\n\nThe strike was designed to be limited in nature and to damage facilities with minimal casualties, the officials made clear.\n\n\u201cEvery precaution was taken to execute this strike with minimal risk to personnel at the airfield,\u201d Capt. Jeff Davis, a Pentagon spokesman, told reporters. \u201cThe strike was a proportional response.\u201d\n\nThe Russian military, which operates from the Shayrat base, was warned ahead of time, Davis said, and the area that the Russians are known to have used was carefully not targeted.\n\nThe U.S. has no plans for additional strikes for now, he added.\n\n\u201cIt will be the regime\u2019s choice if there are any more\u201d military strikes,\u201d Davis said. \u201cAnd it will be based upon their conduct going forward. We do not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against innocent civilians.\u201d\n\nThe action drew mixed responses from leaders of both parties, who have been deeply divided over Syria policy nearly for the length of the country\u2019s civil war.\n\nMembers of Congress who have long argued for more direct U.S. military action against Assad, including Republican Sens. John McCain of Arizona and Marco Rubio of Florida, hailed the attack.\n\nHouse Speaker Paul Ryan (R-Wis.) said the strike \"was appropriate and just.\u201d\n\n\u201cThese tactical strikes make clear that the Assad regime can no longer count on American inaction as it carries out atrocities against the Syrian people,\u201d he said.\n\nHillary Clinton, whom Trump defeated in the presidential election, said in an appearance in New York several hours before the strikes were launched that she had long advocated attacking Syria\u2019s airfields.\n\nBut other Democrats chided Trump for acting without Congress\u2019 approval.\n\nSo did Sen. Rand Paul (R-Ky.). \"While we all condemn the atrocities in Syria, the United States was not attacked,\u201d he said.\n\n\u201cThe President needs Congressional authorization for military action as required by the Constitution, and I call on him to come to Congress for a proper debate.\u201d\n\n\u201cOur prior interventions in this region have done nothing to make us safer, and Syria will be no different,\" he said.\n\nPentagon officials updated their Syria plans after an emergency meeting of the National Security Council late Wednesday, one day after U.S radar and surveillance systems detected a fixed-wing Syrian aircraft drop bombs near a hospital in the rebel-held area around Khan Sheikhoun in Idlib province, officials said.\n\nSoon after the attack, photos and videos emerged on social media that showed lifeless bodies of children, eyes open, sprawled on the ground beside surviving victims with foam bubbling from their mouths as they gasped for air.\n\nThe Joint Chiefs of Staff met Thursday afternoon to consider the crisis and top congressional officials were briefed on the plans. The White House national security advisor, H.R. McMaster, was in Palm Beach with Trump.\n\nWhether the strike Thursday will seriously affect Syria\u2019s capabilities remains to be seen.\n\nAirstrikes on the runways that Syrian forces use to launch bombing missions would have only temporary, minimal impact, experts said.\n\nHelicopters, which Syrian troops have used to drop improvised \u201cbarrel bombs\u201d on civilian targets, can fly from almost anywhere.\n\nComplicating the calculus, more than 1,000 U.S. troops now are deployed in Syria. Many are helping Syrian rebel militias fight against Islamic State, especially as they close in on the group\u2019s stronghold at Raqqah.\n\nThe U.S. attack could make the Americans targets for retaliation from Syrian troops.\n\nIn any case, a \u201cone-off strike\u201d would have no real impact, said Frederic C. Hof, a former Obama administration advisor on Syria and director of the Rafik Hariri Center for the Middle East at the Atlantic Council in Washington.\n\n\u201cIt\u2019s basically telling Assad \u2018Do what you want to civilians, just not with chemicals,\u2019\u201d he said. \u201cWe\u2019ll go back to where we were in 2013.\u201d", "images": ["http://www.trbimg.com/img-58e6f546/turbine/la-na-exxon-valdez-20170406/70/70x70", "http://www.trbimg.com/img-58e6fd31/turbine/la-me-don-rickles-snap-20170406/70/70x70", "http://www.trbimg.com/img-58e70d5d/turbine/la-fg-syria-us-20170406/70/70x70", "http://www.trbimg.com/img-58e70d5d/turbine/la-fg-syria-us-20170406"], "videos": []}
